{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"b53e2049-9d56-45ba-9e02-75703aa3e7cf","content":"On macOS, when a NativeAOT app crashes, look in these locations:\n\n1. **Apple Crash Reports** — The OS automatically generates `.ips` crash reports:\n   ```\n   ~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n   /Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n   ```\n   Files are named like `YourApp_<date>.ips`. Open with any text editor.\n\n2. **Console.app** — Open Console → sidebar → *Crash Reports* to browse them interactively.\n\n3. **Core dumps** — Disabled by default. To enable:\n   ```bash\n   ulimit -c unlimited\n   ```\n   Then re-run your app. Core files land in `/cores/core.<pid>`.\n\n4. **`lldb`** — Attach to analyze a core dump:\n   ```bash\n   lldb --core /cores/core.12345 ./YourApp\n   ```\n\nThe `.ips` crash report is usually the quickest path — it includes the faulting thread, stack trace, and signal info without any extra setup.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"244d236f-3ec9-4004-950d-6d701a3fd4b1","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about finding crash dumps/reports for a NativeAOT app on macOS when `createdump` isn't available. This is a knowledge question, not a code task.","outputTokens":314,"requestId":"2C67:9B616:1773EB8:1A50646:69F94C44"},"id":"185323fd-96aa-4053-aa4b-88f2e742cbe8","timestamp":"2026-05-05T01:47:57.165Z","parentId":"b5574106-34c5-4d72-8ceb-212f3cdc0b9d"}
